# Security Cursor Rules (OWASP Top 10)

## Input Validation
- Validate ALL inputs: request body, query params, headers, file uploads
- Use allowlists (not blocklists) for input validation
- Use schema validation (Zod, Joi, Pydantic) for structured data
- Sanitize HTML output to prevent XSS: use DOMPurify or framework escaping
- Never trust client-side validation alone — always validate server-side

## Authentication
- Hash passwords with bcrypt (cost factor ≥ 12) or Argon2
- Use JWT with short expiration + refresh token rotation
- Implement rate limiting on login endpoints (prevent brute force)
- Use HTTPS everywhere — never transmit credentials over HTTP
- Implement MFA for sensitive operations

## Authorization
- Check permissions on EVERY request (not just UI hiding)
- Use RBAC or ABAC for structured access control
- Verify resource ownership: `user.id === resource.userId`
- DON'T: Rely on obscurity (hiding URLs) as security

## SQL Injection Prevention
- Use parameterized queries or ORM (never concatenate SQL strings)
- Use prepared statements for raw queries
- Validate and sanitize user input before database operations

## Secrets Management
- Store secrets in environment variables or secret manager
- Never commit secrets to version control (.env in .gitignore)
- Rotate secrets regularly
- Use different secrets per environment

## HTTP Security Headers
- `Content-Security-Policy` — Prevent XSS and injection
- `Strict-Transport-Security` — Force HTTPS
- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` — Prevent MIME sniffing
- `X-Frame-Options: DENY` — Prevent clickjacking
- Use `helmet.js` (Node) or equivalent for automatic headers
